WEBVTT

00:01.069 --> 00:03.741
Zoey:
This is Nomi and Phil,

00:03.741 --> 00:06.479
a seemingly average pair
whose relationship

00:06.479 --> 00:09.051
was unconventional,
to say the least.

00:09.051 --> 00:10.989
But it hadn't started that way.

00:10.989 --> 00:13.493
The first time they met
went pretty well.

00:13.493 --> 00:15.632
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

00:15.632 --> 00:19.706
The second time they met
went even better.

00:19.706 --> 00:21.409
♪♪

00:21.409 --> 00:24.315
But it was after
those two magical evenings

00:24.315 --> 00:26.820
that things between them
changed forever.

00:26.820 --> 00:31.162
This is your daughter,
Luna.

00:31.162 --> 00:33.099
Oh.

00:33.099 --> 00:37.274
And the hurt Nomi felt from
Phil's silence never went away.

00:37.274 --> 00:40.447
The idea of having a living,
breathing human being

00:40.447 --> 00:43.554
depending on me was...
starting to freak me out.

00:43.554 --> 00:45.290
[ Inhales,
exhales deeply ]

00:45.290 --> 00:47.227
But I did think about her
every single day.

00:47.227 --> 00:50.467
It's really nice that you
thought about her, Phil.

00:50.467 --> 00:54.342
Look, I know that I handled
things wrong, and I'm sorry.

00:54.342 --> 00:56.112
But I want to try and do
the right thing now

00:56.112 --> 00:58.718
and be a father
to my daughter.

00:58.718 --> 01:00.622
[ Indistinct conversations ]

01:00.622 --> 01:02.792
I need to meet her first
to do that, though.

01:04.228 --> 01:07.167
So...can I?

01:07.167 --> 01:09.238
And with that question,

01:09.238 --> 01:12.411
it felt like Phil was trying to
steer the relationship

01:12.411 --> 01:15.652
out of the unconventional,
right his wrongs,

01:15.652 --> 01:19.425
and bring them
into the functional.

01:20.093 --> 01:23.601
♪ Watch out, world,
I'm grown now ♪

01:23.601 --> 01:25.370
♪ I'm grown ♪

01:25.370 --> 01:27.676
♪ Learn something new
every day ♪

01:27.676 --> 01:30.447
♪ I don't know,
so I'mma feel my way ♪

01:30.447 --> 01:32.852
♪ Got the weight of the world
on me ♪

01:32.852 --> 01:36.125
♪ But no regrets,
this is what I say ♪

01:36.125 --> 01:39.666
♪ Watch out, world,
I'm grown now ♪

01:39.666 --> 01:41.369
♪ I'm grown ♪
♪ You can tell me ♪

01:41.369 --> 01:46.680
♪ My heart beating so loud ♪

01:46.680 --> 01:50.420
♪ Mama, look, I'm grown now ♪

01:50.420 --> 01:52.324
♪ I'm grown ♪

01:52.324 --> 01:55.430
Okay. Let me just fix this.
Okay. I think that looks good.

01:55.430 --> 01:56.900
Okay, baby girl.

01:56.900 --> 01:59.472
Now, you make sure you smile
for your daddy, okay?

01:59.472 --> 02:00.775
Let me see that smile.

02:00.775 --> 02:02.846
Let me see.
Yeah! Just like that.

02:02.846 --> 02:04.583
You know,
they say the first man

02:04.583 --> 02:06.854
a little girl ever falls
in love with is her father.

02:06.854 --> 02:08.891
And for some of us,
it's our uncle.

02:08.891 --> 02:10.595
Yes, it is.
Phil: Hello?

02:10.595 --> 02:13.466
He's here. Okay.
Good luck.

02:13.466 --> 02:15.303
[ Whispering ]
Thank you.

02:15.303 --> 02:16.807
[ Birds chirping ]

02:16.807 --> 02:18.711
Hey.

02:18.711 --> 02:21.717
Phil, this is, um...
this is Luna.

02:21.717 --> 02:26.627
Luna, this is
your f...

02:26.627 --> 02:27.796
Phil.

02:27.796 --> 02:29.398
Hi.

02:29.398 --> 02:32.437
It's so nice to meet you,
Luna.

02:32.437 --> 02:34.776
I brought you something.

02:34.776 --> 02:36.914
It's mine?

02:36.914 --> 02:38.717
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

02:38.717 --> 02:40.855
Mine?
Hi!

02:40.855 --> 02:42.926
Hi.

02:42.926 --> 02:45.297
[ Laughs ]

02:45.297 --> 02:47.502
♪♪

02:47.502 --> 02:50.473
Wow.
This trench coat is amazing.

02:50.473 --> 02:52.411
Yeah? I really don't know
what came over me.

02:52.411 --> 02:54.583
I was just so inspired,
I guess.

02:54.583 --> 02:56.920
You know, I can run downtown,
if you like this sketch,

02:56.920 --> 02:59.693
to get some fabric and make
a prototype of the design.

02:59.693 --> 03:01.362
You got a company card?

03:01.362 --> 03:03.734
No.
Uh, there isn't one.

03:04.603 --> 03:06.239
Petty cash?

03:06.239 --> 03:09.913
I have some cash in a
safety‐deposit box in Brussels.

03:09.913 --> 03:13.253
Okay. What do you do when the
company needs to buy something

03:13.253 --> 03:15.725
for the company
in America?

03:15.725 --> 03:19.733
Well, typically,
Doug and I just overcharge

03:19.733 --> 03:22.939
for one of our parties,
buy what I needed,

03:22.939 --> 03:25.578
and just hope there's
a little surplus left over.

03:25.578 --> 03:26.914
But I'm off Doug.

03:26.914 --> 03:28.483
Then what's the alternative,
Luca?

03:28.483 --> 03:30.220
Because I really
don't understand

03:30.220 --> 03:32.725
how we're gonna make
this company operational

03:32.725 --> 03:33.861
if we're broke.

03:33.861 --> 03:36.633
Broke is a state of mind,
Zoey.

03:36.633 --> 03:38.938
♪♪

03:38.938 --> 03:43.714
I cannot believe I sacrificed
my relationship for this.

03:43.714 --> 03:45.283
[ Register beeping ]

03:45.283 --> 03:46.954
I just don't understand
why it's so weird

03:46.954 --> 03:48.590
to sit on the same side.
[ Sighs ]

03:48.590 --> 03:49.893
Listen,
if you want to sit next to me,

03:49.893 --> 03:51.495
we can go to the counter,
but customarily,

03:51.495 --> 03:53.032
two men don't sit
next to each other in a booth.

03:53.032 --> 03:54.736
You know what?
How about you talk

03:54.736 --> 03:56.540
to your new co‐workers about
this in the break room tomorrow?

03:56.540 --> 03:57.942
Too controversial a topic.

03:57.942 --> 03:59.512
I don't want to draw
any attention to myself

03:59.512 --> 04:00.881
at this new gig,

04:00.881 --> 04:02.652
seeing as I lied on my résumé
to get in there.

04:02.652 --> 04:04.923
Ah! God.
I have so much anxiety.

04:04.923 --> 04:06.526
Maybe I made a mistake.

04:06.526 --> 04:08.597
You need to let that go, man.
Anxiety for what?

04:08.597 --> 04:10.601
So you lied about a misdemeanor.
It happens.

04:10.601 --> 04:11.937
You realize
that the system is designed

04:11.937 --> 04:13.574
to work against
people of color,

04:13.574 --> 04:15.243
especially those who have been
in legal trouble.

04:15.243 --> 04:16.379
So you did
what you had to do.

04:16.379 --> 04:17.648
Yeah.
You're right.

04:17.648 --> 04:18.884
It's not about
how I got the job

04:18.884 --> 04:20.387
but what I do
when I get in there.

04:20.387 --> 04:21.656
Exactly,
so you go in there

04:21.656 --> 04:23.359
and you show them
who Vivek Shah is.

04:23.359 --> 04:24.428
Mm‐hmm.
All right?

04:24.428 --> 04:25.765
Who is Vivek Shah?
Me.

04:25.765 --> 04:26.767
Right.

04:26.767 --> 04:28.737
Is that rhubarb?

04:28.737 --> 04:29.739
There.

04:29.739 --> 04:31.543
[ Mid‐tempo music playing ]

04:31.543 --> 04:33.279
Imagine how much easier
that would've been

04:33.279 --> 04:35.618
if we were seated next
to each other, thigh to thigh.

04:35.618 --> 04:36.853
You know what?
Screw it.

04:36.853 --> 04:38.322
You and the rhubarb,
get over here.

04:38.322 --> 04:39.592
Quickly.
So no one sees.

04:39.592 --> 04:41.462
♪♪

04:41.462 --> 04:43.466
[ Cellphone ringing ]

04:43.466 --> 04:46.439
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

04:46.439 --> 04:47.508
Shit.

04:47.508 --> 04:49.478
Okay.
That was a wake‐up call.

04:49.478 --> 04:51.048
We need to get out
this bed.

04:51.048 --> 04:53.086
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, but I can't help it.

04:53.086 --> 04:55.090
I just like having you
all to myself.

04:55.090 --> 04:56.526
Mm.
[ Laughs ]

04:56.526 --> 04:59.566
I want to take you out,
show you off.

05:00.467 --> 05:03.774
How about you come with me
to the track banquet?

05:03.774 --> 05:06.980
I want you by my side to
celebrate the end of the season.

05:06.980 --> 05:09.017
[ Chuckles ]
Um...

05:09.017 --> 05:12.457
But, you know, but wouldn't that
be, um, a little weird,

05:12.457 --> 05:13.827
being around
my old teammates?

05:13.827 --> 05:17.334
Oh, come on.
Everybody misses you anyway.

05:17.334 --> 05:18.670
Don't make me beg.

05:18.670 --> 05:20.941
[ Chuckles, sighs ]

05:20.941 --> 05:22.979
Fine. Fine.
I'm in.

05:22.979 --> 05:24.949
Hey. Okay.
It's gonna be amazing.

05:24.949 --> 05:27.487
I promise. We're gonna ‐‐
We're gonna drink.

05:27.487 --> 05:29.559
We're gonna dance.
We're gonna turn up.

05:29.559 --> 05:31.495
We're gonna be dressed
to the nines.

05:31.495 --> 05:33.634
It'll be a night
you'll never forget.

05:33.634 --> 05:35.971
Oh, I'm sure I won't.
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

05:35.971 --> 05:40.346
♪ In my house ♪

05:41.616 --> 05:43.486
♪ Everybody's... ♪

05:43.486 --> 05:44.923
So, as time went on,

05:44.923 --> 05:47.962
Nomi gradually found a way
to let Phil in.

05:47.962 --> 05:51.570
They had fallen into a routine,
with trips to the park,

05:51.570 --> 05:56.913
story time at the library, and
family picnics in the backyard.

05:56.913 --> 05:59.919
Okay, so, I'm, um,
actually in the process

05:59.919 --> 06:01.823
of planning Luna's
second birthday party.

06:01.823 --> 06:05.396
And I was wondering
if maybe you wanted to come

06:05.396 --> 06:08.069
and, like, invite your family
or ‐‐

06:08.069 --> 06:09.772
Absolutely.
Yeah.

06:09.772 --> 06:11.008
Yeah?

06:11.008 --> 06:12.878
When were you thinking?
Uh, the 14th.

06:12.878 --> 06:16.519
Her birthday ‐‐ you know,
the day my body changed forever.

06:16.519 --> 06:18.924
[ Luna shouting indistinctly ]
Shoot. The 14th.

06:18.924 --> 06:20.861
Yeah.
Is that a problem?

06:20.861 --> 06:23.466
Uh, no.
[ Footsteps approaching ]

06:23.466 --> 06:25.904
Well, actually, y‐yeah.

06:25.904 --> 06:27.975
I'm ‐‐
I'm gonna be out of town.

06:27.975 --> 06:29.979
It's something
that's been planned for a while,

06:29.979 --> 06:32.785
but I already booked my flight,
so...

06:32.785 --> 06:35.791
Is there any way we could do it,
like, the weekend after

06:35.791 --> 06:37.093
or even the Monday after?

06:37.093 --> 06:39.498
I get back
late Sunday night.
Yeah. No.

06:39.498 --> 06:41.503
This is also something I've been
planning for a while ‐‐

06:41.503 --> 06:43.573
like, since her first birthday,
and I'm kind of a stickler

06:43.573 --> 06:45.944
for celebrating a birthday
on a birthday, so...

06:45.944 --> 06:48.617
No, no, no. Totally.
I‐I‐I totally get that.

06:48.617 --> 06:50.854
But, um, I promise I'll get her
a great gift.

06:50.854 --> 06:52.390
Cool.
Hey, honey.

06:52.390 --> 06:53.960
And of course I'm happy
to go half on the party.

06:53.960 --> 06:55.798
No.
It doesn't even matter.

06:55.798 --> 06:57.535
I mean, she's probably not even
gonna know the difference.

06:57.535 --> 06:59.839
I'm gonna get you more juice,
okay, baby?

06:59.839 --> 07:01.408
Yeah.
Okay.
I'll be right back.

07:01.408 --> 07:02.945
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

07:04.782 --> 07:08.724
Mm. I snapped photos of you guys
through the window.

07:08.724 --> 07:11.428
Super adorable.
Hang on. Let me find them.

07:11.428 --> 07:13.567
Oh, there's one of Phil
giving Luna a piggyback ride

07:13.567 --> 07:15.838
that you could totally use
for your family Hanukkah card.

07:15.838 --> 07:16.973
Okay.
Ana, just stop.

07:16.973 --> 07:18.677
It's weird
and it's stalkery,

07:18.677 --> 07:20.948
and we're not even close to
the family‐holiday‐card stage.

07:20.948 --> 07:23.687
Oh, but look how cute.
[ Luna crying ]

07:23.687 --> 07:25.758
Oh, my God. What happened?
What happened? What happened?

07:25.758 --> 07:27.026
It's okay, it's okay,
it's okay.

07:27.026 --> 07:28.730
I was checking a text,
and she fell.

07:28.730 --> 07:30.066
It's just a bump.

07:30.066 --> 07:32.170
I promise she's fine.
What are you thinking?

07:32.170 --> 07:33.874
You can't take your eyes
off of a toddler.

07:33.874 --> 07:35.744
It was a mistake.
I'm sorry.
No. You know what?

07:35.744 --> 07:37.080
This whole thing is a mistake.
Just go.

07:37.080 --> 07:38.950
Just go. Just go.
What?

07:38.950 --> 07:40.621
Just go!
Phil, go!

07:40.621 --> 07:41.689
You're serious?

07:41.689 --> 07:43.660
I'm serious. Go.

07:43.660 --> 07:45.664
[ Crying continues ]
It's okay. I know.

07:45.664 --> 07:48.436
I know. I know.
I know. I know.

07:48.436 --> 07:50.507
I know. I know.

07:50.507 --> 07:51.743
You're tired.

07:57.220 --> 07:59.224
And how long do you plan
on keeping Phil on ice

07:59.224 --> 08:00.694
for a simple accident?

08:00.694 --> 08:02.798
Mm, probably until she forgets
who he is.

08:02.798 --> 08:05.470
Gosh.
Nomi, come on.

08:05.470 --> 08:07.440
He is trying.

08:07.440 --> 08:10.848
It was one little accident that
could've happened to anyone.

08:10.848 --> 08:13.587
Aren't you being
just a little ridiculous?

08:13.587 --> 08:16.926
Okay. Ana, seriously.
What's wrong with you?

08:16.926 --> 08:18.797
Are you my best friend
or are you his best friend?

08:18.797 --> 08:20.667
That's a stupid question.
Is it?

08:20.667 --> 08:22.203
It doesn't really feel like it,
because

08:22.203 --> 08:24.140
ever since I got pregnant,
you've been riding for this guy.

08:24.140 --> 08:26.913
Obviously, my loyalty is to you
and your baby.

08:26.913 --> 08:29.184
But part of that loyalty
is being honest

08:29.184 --> 08:32.625
and to encourage you to do
what's best for all of you.
Mm.

08:32.625 --> 08:34.562
Look, after seeing
how much happier you've been

08:34.562 --> 08:38.469
as a little family rather than
a single mother, I‐I‐I just ‐‐

08:38.469 --> 08:40.172
Look, I think
you're making a mistake

08:40.172 --> 08:43.279
with this whole
Phil situation.

08:43.279 --> 08:47.621
Look, I hinged the fate of my
graduation on this internship,

08:47.621 --> 08:50.293
so I am coming to you
for help.

08:50.293 --> 08:51.996
But why?

08:51.996 --> 08:54.234
Because you're the person
that could really bridge

08:54.234 --> 08:56.973
the gap of communication
between Doug and your brother.

08:56.973 --> 08:58.810
But why would I do that
for you?

08:58.810 --> 09:03.452
Obviously because you're
a strong Black woman

09:03.452 --> 09:07.595
who wants to see another strong
Black woman succeed, sister.

09:07.595 --> 09:10.499
Mm.
Okay. Uh, Zoey...

09:10.499 --> 09:11.669
Mm‐hmm?

09:11.669 --> 09:13.205
...please don't
race‐card me.

09:13.205 --> 09:14.976
Mm‐hmm.
Also, I've noticed
a pattern

09:14.976 --> 09:19.050
where you're constantly dragging
my brother into your drama,

09:19.050 --> 09:22.290
and now you're trying to do it
to me, and I'm just ‐‐

09:22.290 --> 09:25.296
I'm not down with that, so, um,
you can go find yourself

09:25.296 --> 09:29.270
another strong Black woman
to guilt into helping you.

09:29.270 --> 09:32.176
Well, a little birdie told me
that somebody named Kiela

09:32.176 --> 09:33.880
played a pretty big role

09:33.880 --> 09:35.951
in why Doug and Luca aren't cool
right now.

09:35.951 --> 09:37.988
So I guess
we're both responsible

09:37.988 --> 09:40.661
for dragging your brother
into some drama.

09:40.661 --> 09:43.132
I'll be borrowing these.
Thank you.

09:43.132 --> 09:45.236
[ Mid‐tempo music plays ]

09:45.236 --> 09:48.008
♪♪

09:50.747 --> 09:52.216
Okay.
Here's what happened.

09:52.216 --> 09:54.789
The new job was going great ‐‐
until it wasn't.

09:54.789 --> 09:56.158
♪♪

09:56.158 --> 09:57.961
Ding‐dong!
What up, boy‐boy?

09:57.961 --> 09:59.732
You Vivek?
Yeah.

09:59.732 --> 10:02.103
I'm Matt, your new supervisor.
Just wanted to introduce myself.

10:02.103 --> 10:03.840
Cool.
Um, nice to meet you.

10:03.840 --> 10:05.911
I'm excited to be part
of the User Interface team

10:05.911 --> 10:07.013
and code for you guys.

10:08.182 --> 10:09.885
Wait.
Do I know you from somewhere?

10:09.885 --> 10:11.321
You do not.

10:11.321 --> 10:13.258
Oh, Ding Dong definitely knows
his boy‐boy ‐‐

10:13.258 --> 10:14.962
from the copious amount
of drug‐drugs

10:14.962 --> 10:16.098
I'd previously sold him.

10:16.098 --> 10:17.668
Ding Dong boy‐boy?

10:17.668 --> 10:19.237
What kind of workplace
is this, man?

10:19.237 --> 10:21.843
One where it seems my past
is gonna keep haunting me.

10:21.843 --> 10:23.212
I don't see how, though.

10:23.212 --> 10:25.049
Listen, if this guy figures
you're the one

10:25.049 --> 10:27.120
that sold him drugs, right,
what can he even say?

10:27.120 --> 10:29.992
He bought the drugs.
So you cancel each other out.

10:29.992 --> 10:31.094
You're right.

10:31.094 --> 10:33.232
Yeah. I know.

10:33.232 --> 10:35.202
[ Gasps ]
Okay.

10:35.202 --> 10:38.142
Now, this is giving me
"cover of GQ" vibes.

10:38.142 --> 10:40.212
This would be perfect
for the banquet.

10:40.212 --> 10:42.116
Mm, I don't know.

10:42.116 --> 10:46.324
I am thinking of something
more along the lines of this.

10:46.324 --> 10:48.797
Mm.
That look is so overdone.

10:48.797 --> 10:50.065
I feel like all the guys

10:50.065 --> 10:52.003
are gonna be wearing dresses
that night,

10:52.003 --> 10:54.842
and I feel like wearing pants
would make more of a statement.

10:54.842 --> 10:57.246
[ Laughs ]
Y‐You're kidding, right?
I don't know.

10:57.246 --> 10:59.718
I think you should go
a little more GQ

10:59.718 --> 11:01.823
and a little less
Glamour magazine.

11:01.823 --> 11:03.425
Okay.

11:03.425 --> 11:06.264
This is an odd conversation I'm
sensing has a little more to it.

11:06.264 --> 11:08.168
So what's the deal?
Seriously.

11:08.168 --> 11:10.206
Uh, okay.

11:11.809 --> 11:15.149
I really was trying not to say
anything,

11:15.149 --> 11:19.257
but the night when we hung out
and you showed up in a dress,

11:19.257 --> 11:22.196
that was very surprising
for me.

11:22.196 --> 11:24.768
And usually surprises
are a really good thing,

11:24.768 --> 11:28.710
but in that case...
it was a very confusing thing.

11:28.710 --> 11:33.051
Got it.
You had a problem with my dress.

11:33.051 --> 11:34.354
I did.

11:34.354 --> 11:35.957
I do.

11:35.957 --> 11:39.397
And ‐‐ And ‐‐ And I know
that's really messed up.

11:39.397 --> 11:41.401
I‐I just have
really conflicted feelings

11:41.401 --> 11:43.372
about dating a guy
who wears a dress.

11:45.409 --> 11:47.915
Look, this is my issue.
This isn't your issue.

11:47.915 --> 11:50.252
I just need some more time
to plow through it,

11:50.252 --> 11:52.156
and I'll be fine.

11:53.358 --> 11:55.296
[ Mid‐tempo music plays ]

11:55.296 --> 11:57.199
All right.
Cool.

11:57.199 --> 11:59.838
If it makes you
more comfortable...

11:59.838 --> 12:01.909
I'll wear the suit.

12:01.909 --> 12:02.911
Seriously?

12:02.911 --> 12:04.447
Yeah.
It's not a big deal.

12:04.447 --> 12:07.721
Oh, thank you.
I really appreciate it.

12:07.721 --> 12:09.257
Thank you.
[ Laughs ]

12:09.257 --> 12:11.127
Broccoli?

12:12.229 --> 12:14.334
[ Knock on door ]

12:15.737 --> 12:17.473
Hold on a sec.

12:20.012 --> 12:21.348
Hey.

12:21.348 --> 12:22.818
What are you doing here?

12:22.818 --> 12:24.722
Uh, I came here
to see Luna.

12:24.722 --> 12:25.857
[ Luna laughs ]

12:25.857 --> 12:28.095
Without asking me first?

12:28.095 --> 12:29.497
Don't do that.

12:29.497 --> 12:31.134
I called you.
I texted you.

12:31.134 --> 12:33.038
You didn't respond.
Oh. Okay.

12:33.038 --> 12:35.409
I'm sorry I wasn't able to check
in and validate your schedule.

12:35.409 --> 12:37.446
I don't really have
a lot of time as a single mom.

12:37.446 --> 12:39.050
Not that you would know,

12:39.050 --> 12:40.854
but I have to get her ready
in the morning,

12:40.854 --> 12:42.958
put her to sleep at night,
um, plan her birthday party.

12:42.958 --> 12:44.360
So that's
what this is about?

12:44.360 --> 12:46.297
The fact that I can't be here
for her birthday?

12:46.297 --> 12:47.868
No, it's not.

12:47.868 --> 12:49.370
It's about the fact
that you're choosing

12:49.370 --> 12:51.041
not to make it
to her birthday party.

12:51.041 --> 12:52.811
You don't just get to
cherry‐pick as a parent.

12:52.811 --> 12:54.380
You have to show up
every single day.

12:54.380 --> 12:57.988
And so far ‐‐ so far,
you've been really bad at that.

12:57.988 --> 12:59.792
Well, I think we could agree
that part of that

12:59.792 --> 13:01.094
was you keeping her a secret
from me

13:01.094 --> 13:02.296
for the first six months
of her life.

13:02.296 --> 13:04.100
Oh, okay.

13:04.100 --> 13:06.872
So should I just not, you know,
depend on you for anything,

13:06.872 --> 13:08.241
let you off the hook
from all your responsibilities,

13:08.241 --> 13:09.845
and never depend on you
for anything ever?

13:09.845 --> 13:11.481
[ Luna coughing, choking ]
Wait. Is she choking?

13:11.481 --> 13:12.951
What?
Luna.

13:12.951 --> 13:14.788
Luna! Luna!

13:14.788 --> 13:17.059
[ Whimpers, coughs ]

13:17.059 --> 13:19.330
♪♪

13:19.330 --> 13:22.002
[ Exhales deeply ]
It's okay.

13:22.002 --> 13:25.209
You're okay?
It's okay.

13:25.209 --> 13:27.313
Shh.

13:31.956 --> 13:34.026
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

13:34.026 --> 13:35.830
[ Knock, door opens ]

13:35.830 --> 13:38.435
Hey.
How's my sweet little girl?

13:38.435 --> 13:39.538
Nomi:
She's good.

13:39.538 --> 13:42.076
Good.
And how's Luna?

13:43.011 --> 13:47.052
It was really scary,
and...

13:47.052 --> 13:50.058
I was an asshole to Phil
and to you.

13:50.058 --> 13:52.196
And I'm sorry.
Oh, sweetie, it's okay.

13:52.196 --> 13:54.000
You're always an asshole.

13:55.469 --> 13:57.106
Oh.

13:57.106 --> 14:00.012
I hate seeing you
like this.

14:00.012 --> 14:01.080
She's good.

14:01.080 --> 14:03.385
Okay.
[ Sniffles ]

14:03.385 --> 14:05.990
So, it says here
we can make some serious money

14:05.990 --> 14:07.928
just letting strangers
on the Internet

14:07.928 --> 14:09.831
watch us eat
a large spaghetti dinner.

14:09.831 --> 14:10.833
Sounds legit.

14:10.833 --> 14:13.104
Yeah.

14:13.104 --> 14:15.309
Hey.
Luca: What's up?

14:15.309 --> 14:17.914
We need to talk.

14:17.914 --> 14:19.885
Hey, uh, can we have the room
for a minute?

14:19.885 --> 14:22.256
Yeah. I should probably
be heading out anyway.

14:22.256 --> 14:25.395
And, uh, Luca, I'll grab those
antacids for spaghetti dinner.

14:25.395 --> 14:26.599
Yeah?
Okay.

14:26.599 --> 14:28.401
Thank you.

14:31.107 --> 14:33.278
Can I ask you something?

14:33.278 --> 14:35.917
So, do you just, like,
not want to win?

14:35.917 --> 14:38.522
[ Sighs ]
What are you talking about?

14:38.522 --> 14:40.425
Doug and I are having, like,
this little fling,

14:40.425 --> 14:42.363
and you're just not gonna make
the money you need

14:42.363 --> 14:44.433
to operate your company?

14:44.433 --> 14:46.237
I mean, I still got
this Brussels thing.

14:46.237 --> 14:47.540
Luca, come on.

14:47.540 --> 14:49.978
I‐I'm sorry for the part
I played in all this.

14:49.978 --> 14:52.383
But you got to stop letting
these petty differences

14:52.383 --> 14:55.455
get in the way of you
and your bag.

14:55.455 --> 14:57.527
Give me your phone.
What? Why?

14:57.527 --> 15:00.365
Just give me it.
Come on.

15:00.365 --> 15:02.871
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

15:02.871 --> 15:08.014
♪♪

15:08.014 --> 15:10.252
It's that easy.

15:10.252 --> 15:12.256
Just hit "send."

15:12.256 --> 15:19.370
♪♪

15:19.370 --> 15:21.240
[ Cellphone chimes ]

15:21.240 --> 15:22.944
♪♪

15:22.944 --> 15:24.347
So, how'd it go
at the job?

15:24.347 --> 15:25.683
Did homeboy realize
you were his dealer or what?

15:25.683 --> 15:27.654
Sure did,
and to make matters worse,

15:27.654 --> 15:29.524
he wants me to hook him up
again.

15:29.524 --> 15:31.027
Mm. Sounds like something
boy‐boy would do.

15:31.027 --> 15:32.530
Right?
Yeah.

15:32.530 --> 15:35.435
And I thought my biggest issue
was lying on my résumé.

15:35.435 --> 15:37.339
Now I have
the added wrinkle

15:37.339 --> 15:40.212
of my supervisor wanting me
to sell him coke.

15:40.212 --> 15:42.249
Well, why don't you just
tell him you're out the game?

15:43.451 --> 15:45.188
Yeah, right.

15:45.188 --> 15:48.027
I don't think it's smart
to make an enemy out of my boss.

15:48.027 --> 15:49.463
What if he starts
poking around

15:49.463 --> 15:51.602
about why I took
this modestly paying desk job

15:51.602 --> 15:54.240
instead of dealing drugs and
making racks and racks of dough?

15:54.240 --> 15:55.676
Mm‐hmm.
He'd immediately know

15:55.676 --> 15:58.716
I was lying on my résumé
about the misdemeanor,

15:58.716 --> 16:02.122
about the degree,
about my proficiency in Excel

16:02.122 --> 16:03.626
and my fluency
in Cantonese.

16:03.626 --> 16:05.596
It's like a house of cards,
man.
Okay.

16:05.596 --> 16:08.201
So, I mean, there's only
one option here.
Clearly.

16:08.201 --> 16:09.905
I have to sell him
a bad batch of drugs

16:09.905 --> 16:11.274
and hope his heart stops.

16:11.274 --> 16:13.344
Or just, you know,
come clean.

16:13.344 --> 16:15.182
That's what I
was gonna say.

16:15.182 --> 16:17.554
Just go to him, be the nice
little brown boy that you are,

16:17.554 --> 16:19.991
and say, "Hey, look, the odds
were stacked against me.

16:19.991 --> 16:22.496
I had no choice but to lie,"
and he will totally understand.

16:22.496 --> 16:23.966
Mm.

16:25.035 --> 16:27.072
What am I saying? You're right.
You got to kill him.

16:27.072 --> 16:29.176
Yeah.

16:29.176 --> 16:31.582
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

16:31.582 --> 16:36.057
♪♪

16:36.057 --> 16:37.660
Des:
What's good?

16:37.660 --> 16:42.670
♪♪

16:42.670 --> 16:44.440
[ Music stops ]

16:44.440 --> 16:46.477
[ Indistinct conversations ]

16:46.477 --> 16:50.018
Hey.
Uh, I...

16:50.018 --> 16:51.087
I‐I didn't think ‐‐

16:51.087 --> 16:52.557
I know what you thought.

16:52.557 --> 16:54.694
And I really,
really wanted to wear

16:54.694 --> 16:56.264
that tux you picked out
for me

16:56.264 --> 16:59.504
and to show up to the formal
with you on my arm

16:59.504 --> 17:01.173
and for us to have
an amazing night.

17:01.173 --> 17:04.981
But putting on
what you wanted me to wear

17:04.981 --> 17:06.518
instead of what I
wanted to wear

17:06.518 --> 17:09.189
took the amazing
out of everything.

17:11.127 --> 17:14.066
And as much
as I'm feeling you,

17:14.066 --> 17:16.404
I don't think I could be with
someone who doesn't accept me.

17:17.607 --> 17:20.478
It's just...
I have one hang‐up,

17:20.478 --> 17:24.386
and I‐I said I'm going to be
working on it.

17:24.386 --> 17:26.257
But I'm good
with who you are.

17:26.257 --> 17:29.263
Look, I know you're good with me
being into all types of people,

17:29.263 --> 17:33.672
but...it's the dress thing
you seem to be so stuck on.

17:34.741 --> 17:38.816
And that's also a part of who
I am and how I express myself.

17:38.816 --> 17:43.358
And...
I'm happy with all of me,

17:43.358 --> 17:47.165
a‐and I don't want to wait
for someone who isn't.

17:47.165 --> 17:50.071
Des, I‐I think you're taking
all of this the wrong way.

17:50.071 --> 17:51.140
Fine.

17:51.140 --> 17:52.677
If I am...

17:52.677 --> 17:57.720
come with me to the banquet
like this, as I am.

17:57.720 --> 18:00.058
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

18:01.695 --> 18:03.732
I'm s‐‐ I'm sorry.

18:05.235 --> 18:07.573
That's, uh,
that's what I thought.

18:11.313 --> 18:14.554
You ‐‐ You really do
look beautiful tonight.

18:16.490 --> 18:22.503
♪♪

18:22.503 --> 18:28.481
♪♪

18:28.481 --> 18:30.085
[ Birds chirping ]

18:30.085 --> 18:32.089
♪♪

18:32.089 --> 18:34.093
Hey.
Hey.

18:34.093 --> 18:36.565
Thanks for stopping by.

18:36.565 --> 18:38.569
What time's your flight?

18:38.569 --> 18:42.242
Uh...actually,
I'm not going.

18:42.242 --> 18:45.716
Uh, can I help you
with these?

18:45.716 --> 18:49.691
Look, I wanted to apologize
for everything.

18:49.691 --> 18:52.262
I, uh, should not
have flipped out on you

18:52.262 --> 18:55.168
over what was seriously
just an accident,

18:55.168 --> 18:58.141
and, um, it was ‐‐
it was way out of line.

18:59.176 --> 19:00.513
I appreciate that,

19:00.513 --> 19:04.521
but I was being stupid
about the birthday thing.

19:04.521 --> 19:08.394
Obviously, I'm...
I'm not a good parent yet,

19:08.394 --> 19:10.666
but I'm trying.

19:10.666 --> 19:12.269
Yeah, I know.

19:12.269 --> 19:15.709
And honestly,
I could see you trying.

19:15.709 --> 19:19.584
You know, the last few weeks
together felt really nice,

19:19.584 --> 19:26.832
like a weird little family,
which...scared me,

19:26.832 --> 19:28.702
'cause I was like,

19:28.702 --> 19:33.411
you know, "What if I get used to
this and ‐‐ and it goes away?"

19:33.411 --> 19:40.593
So I did what I always do,
which is...I lashed out.

19:40.593 --> 19:43.231
Look, I get being scared.

19:43.899 --> 19:48.174
I mean, this whole situation
is freakin' terrifying.

19:49.309 --> 19:51.581
Yeah, it is.

19:54.520 --> 19:56.390
What's this?

19:56.390 --> 19:59.597
That is
Luna's birthday gift.

20:01.433 --> 20:05.709
You got her a...studio apartment
on Riverside?

20:05.709 --> 20:08.749
No, I got me a studio apartment
on Riverside.

20:10.686 --> 20:14.527
That way, I can practice
being a dad day to day.

20:14.527 --> 20:16.363
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

20:16.363 --> 20:19.403
This is Nomi and Phil.

20:19.403 --> 20:24.313
So after a sexy one‐night stand
followed by a baby bomb drop,

20:24.313 --> 20:26.618
a yearlong rift,
and then a few rocky weeks

20:26.618 --> 20:29.924
of getting reacquainted,
Nomi finally got it right.

20:29.924 --> 20:32.596
She learned how to step
out of her own way

20:32.596 --> 20:35.602
and give her and her daughter
a chance at happiness

20:35.602 --> 20:37.640
by allowing Phil in

20:37.640 --> 20:41.681
and letting the three of them
become their own little family.

20:41.681 --> 20:43.885
♪♪

20:47.359 --> 20:49.864
Okay. You ready?
Yeah.

20:49.864 --> 20:52.035
We don't have to "Lady and the
Tramp" this stuff, now, do we?

20:52.035 --> 20:53.672
Oh. No.
Obviously not.

20:53.672 --> 20:55.709
They'd have to pay extra
for that, which they didn't.

20:55.709 --> 20:59.449
So forks up.
We are going live.

21:00.351 --> 21:01.821
Okay.

21:01.821 --> 21:04.660
[ Siren wailing,
horns honking in distance ]

21:04.660 --> 21:07.399
Mmm!

21:07.399 --> 21:14.747
Wow. This spaghetti
and meatballs is so delicious!

21:14.747 --> 21:16.551
Yeah.
[ Clears throat ]

21:16.551 --> 21:19.256
I'm very much enjoying
this dinner you've made me.

21:19.256 --> 21:21.761
[ Computer chiming ]

21:21.761 --> 21:24.700
[ Down‐tempo music plays ]

21:24.700 --> 21:28.374
♪♪

21:28.374 --> 21:31.413
[ Whispering ]
Hey, Luca.

21:31.413 --> 21:34.019
I think this is kind of sexual
for them.

21:34.019 --> 21:36.791
Yeah.
Of course it is.

21:36.791 --> 21:41.734
So you gonna rub that meatball
in my face or...

21:41.734 --> 21:45.007
♪♪
